the following bacterial families most commonly demonstrates carbapenem resistance in urinary tract infections?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Clostridiaceae","Bacteroidaceae","Streptococcaceae","Enterobacteriaceae","Helicobacteraceae"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EEnterobacteriaceae\u003C/strong\u003E family includes many common urinary tract pathogens such as \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EKlebsiella\u003C/em\u003E species. Carbapenem resistance in this family is of particular concern due to their frequent involvement in urinary tract infections and limited alternative treatment options.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClostridiaceae\u003C/strong\u003E primarily cause gastrointestinal infections and are not typically associated with urinary tract infections\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacteroidaceae\u003C/strong\u003E are anaerobic organisms that rarely cause urinary tract infections\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcaceae\u003C/strong\u003E more commonly cause respiratory and skin infections rather than urinary tract infections\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHelicobacteraceae\u003C/strong\u003E primarily cause gastric infections and are not urinary pathogens\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECarbapenem-resistant Enterobacteriaceae can spread resistance genes to other bacteria and are associated with high mortality rates when causing invasive infections.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Enterobacteriaceae are the most common cause of urinary tract infections and increasing carbapenem resistance is a major clinical concern.","Carbapenem-resistant Enterobacteriaceae (CRE) are considered urgent threats due to limited treatment options.","Common Enterobacteriaceae causing UTIs include Escherichia coli and Klebsiella species."],"references":["Freire MP, Mendes CV, Piovesan AC, de Paula FJ, Spad\u00e3o F, Nahas WC, David-Neto E, Pierrotti LC. Does the urinary tract infection caused by carbapenem-resistant Gram-negative bacilli impact the outcome of kidney transplant recipients? Transpl Infect Dis. 2018 Aug;20(4):e12923. doi: 10.1111/tid.12923. Epub 2018 Jun 13. PMID: 29797681.","Zilberberg MD, Nathanson BH, Sulham K, Fan W, Shorr AF. Carbapenem resistance, inappropriate empiric treatment and outcomes among patients hospitalized with Enterobacteriaceae urinary tract infection, pneumonia and sepsis. BMC Infect Dis. 2017 Apr 17;17(1):279. doi: 10.1186/s12879-017-2383-z. PMID: 28415969; PMCID: PMC5393012.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53536"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15143"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53536"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-08T21:36:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T10:16:59+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7831"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68079"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"des